# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: homebrew-macos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew has made extensive use of GitHub to expand the support of several packages through user contributions.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In 2010, Homebrew was the third-most-forked repository on GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In 2012, Homebrew had the largest number of new contributors on GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In 2013, Homebrew had both the largest number of contributors and issues closed of any project on GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew has spawned several sub-projects such as Linuxbrew, a Linux port now officially merged into Homebrew; Homebrew Cask, which builds upon Homebrew and focuses on the installation of GUI applications; and "taps" dedicated to specific areas or programming languages like PHP.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew was written by Max Howell in 2009.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In March 2013, Homebrew successfully completed a Kickstarter campaign to raise funds for servers to test and build formulae and managed to raise £14,859.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On December 13, 2013, the Homebrew repository migrated from Howell's GitHub account to its own project account.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In February 2015, due to downtime at SourceForge which resulted in binaries being unavailable, Homebrew moved their hosting to Bintray.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On September 21, 2016, Homebrew version 1.0.0 was released.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] In January 2019, Linuxbrew was merged back into Homebrew, adding beta support for Linux and the Windows Subsystem for Linux to the Homebrew feature set.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On February 2, 2019, Homebrew version 2.0.0 was released.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On September 21, 2020, Homebrew version 2.5.2 was released with support for bottle taps (binary package repositories) via GitHub Releases.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Version 3.0.0 was released almost exactly two years after 2.0.0, on February 5, 2021, and added official support for Macs with Apple silicon.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] As of February 2021, Homebrew is maintained by a team of 34 people.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On April 12, 2021, Homebrew version 3.1.0 was released completing their migration of bottles (binary packages) to GitHub Packages before the May 1, 2021 shutdown of Bintray as previously announced by JFrog.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] On February 16, 2023, Homebrew version 4.0.0 was released which defaults to fetching Homebrew-maintained formulae from hosted JSON files rather than local Git-cloned taps.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew is written in the Ruby programming language and targets the version of Ruby that comes installed with the macOS operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] By default, it is installed into `/usr/local` on Intel-based machines and `/opt/homebrew` on Apple silicon.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] The installation consists of a Git repository that enables users to update Homebrew by pulling an updated repository from GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] The package manager builds software from source using "formulae", Ruby scripts constructed with the Homebrew domain-specific language (DSL) for managing dependencies, downloading source files, and configuring and compiling software.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Binary packages called "bottles" provide pre-built formulae with default options.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew does not honor the default privileges of `/usr/local`; directory ownership is changed from root with group permissions for the wheel group to the installing user and the "admin" group.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Specifically, the mode changes from `drwxr-xr-x root wheel` to `drwxrwxr-x myuser admin`.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] All files, not just the directories, have their ownership changed by the installer.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] This is considered by some as a major security flaw.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew collects installation, build error, and operating system version statistics via InfluxDB.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] As of Homebrew 4.0.23, no data is collected via Google Analytics.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Users can view analytics data from the last 30, 90, and 365 days on the Homebrew website.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] It is possible to opt out of data collection with the command `brew analytics off`.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew typically supports macOS versions for which Apple still releases security updates, *i.e.*, the current major version of macOS as well as the two previous (major) versions.
[src:homebrew-macos/homebrew-package-manager] As of June 2026 this included macOS 14 Sonoma, macOS 15 Sequoia, macOS 26 Tahoe, and MacOS 27 Golden Gate.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Mac OS X succeeded the classic Mac OS, the primary Macintosh operating system from 1984 to 2001.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Its underlying architecture came from NeXT's NeXTSTEP, as a result of Apple's acquisition of NeXT, which also brought Steve Jobs back to Apple.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The first desktop version, Mac OS X 10.0, was released on March 24, 2001.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apart from OS X Lion, all versions from Mac OS X Leopard onwards are UNIX 03 certified.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Each of Apple's other contemporary operating systems, including iOS, iPadOS, watchOS, tvOS, audioOS and visionOS, are derivatives of macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] During its history, macOS has supported three major processor architectures: the initial version supported PowerPC-based Macs only, with support for Intel-based Macs beginning with OS X Tiger 10.4.4 and support for ARM-based Apple silicon Macs beginning with macOS Big Sur.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Support for PowerPC-based Macs was dropped with OS X Snow Leopard, and it was announced at the 2025 Worldwide Developers Conference that macOS Tahoe will be the last to support Intel-based Macs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Unlike versions of the classic Mac OS, Mac OS X retained the same major version number (10) for almost two decades, with major releases only incrementing the *minor* version number (e.g.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Since 2020, Apple increments the major version component in each major release, with macOS Big Sur getting version number 11.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, the numbering scheme was changed once again, now using the number of the year that follows the release year (e.g. macOS Tahoe, released in September 2025, has a version number 26).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] A prominent part of macOS's original brand identity was the use of the Roman numeral X, pronounced "ten", as well as code naming each release after species of big cats, and later, places within California.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple shortened the name to "OS X" in 2011 and then changed it to "macOS" in 2016 to align with the branding of Apple's other operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2020, macOS Big Sur was presented as version 11—a marked departure after 16 releases of macOS 10—but the naming convention continued to reference places within California.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, Apple unified the version number across all of its products to align with the year after their WWDC announcement, so the release announced at the 2025 WWDC, macOS Tahoe, is macOS 26.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The heritage of what would become macOS originated at NeXT, a company founded by Steve Jobs following his departure from Apple in 1985.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] There, the Unix-like NeXTSTEP operating system was developed, before being launched in 1989.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The kernel of NeXTSTEP is based upon the Mach kernel, which was originally developed at Carnegie Mellon University, with additional kernel layers and low-level user space code derived from parts of FreeBSD and other BSD operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Its graphical user interface was built on top of an object-oriented GUI toolkit using the Objective-C programming language.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Throughout the 1990s, Apple had tried to create a "next-generation" OS to succeed its classic Mac OS through the Taligent, Copland and Gershwin projects; however, all were eventually abandoned.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This led Apple to acquire NeXT in 1997, allowing NeXTSTEP, later called OPENSTEP, to serve as the basis for Apple's next-generation operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The acquisition also led to Steve Jobs returning to Apple as interim and later permanent CEO, shepherding the transformation of the programmer-friendly OPENSTEP into a system that would be adopted by Apple's primary market of home users and creative professionals.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The project was codenamed "Rhapsody" before being officially named Mac OS X.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The "X" in Mac OS X's name represents the Roman numeral for the number ten, and Apple has stated that it should be pronounced "ten" in this context; it is also commonly pronounced like the letter "X".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The iPhone X, iPhone XR and iPhone XS all later followed this convention.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The first version of Mac OS X, Mac OS X Server 1.0, was a transitional product, featuring an interface resembling the classic Mac OS, though it was not compatible with software designed for the older system; consumer releases of Mac OS X included more backward compatibility.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Mac OS applications could be rewritten to run natively via the Carbon API, with many alternatively able to be run directly through the Classic Environment albeit with a reduction in performance.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The consumer version of Mac OS X was launched in March 2001 with Mac OS X 10.0.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Reviews were variable, with many praising its sophisticated, glossy Aqua interface, but criticizing it for sluggish performance.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] With Apple's popularity at a low, the developer of FrameMaker, Adobe Inc., declined to develop new versions of it for Mac OS X.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] *Ars Technica* columnist John Siracusa, who reviewed every major OS X release up to 10.10, described the early releases in retrospect as "dog-slow, feature poor" and Aqua as "unbearably slow and a huge resource hog".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple rapidly developed several new releases of Mac OS X.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple released Mac OS X 10.1 in October 2001, delivering quality of life enhancements.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Beginning in January 2002, Apple preinstalled Mac OS X as the default operating system on all Macs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Later that year Apple released Mac OS X Jaguar (version 10.2), the first version to publicly use its code name in marketing and advertisements.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] As the operating system evolved, it moved away from the classic Mac OS, with applications being added and removed.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Considering music to be a key market, Apple developed the iPod music player and music software for the Mac, including iTunes and GarageBand.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Targeting the consumer and media markets, Apple emphasized its new "digital lifestyle" applications such as the iLife suite, integrated home entertainment through the Front Row media center and the Safari web browser.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] With the increasing popularity of the internet, Apple offered additional online services, including the .Mac, MobileMe, and later, iCloud products.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It later began selling third-party applications through the Mac App Store.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Newer versions of Mac OS X also included modifications to the general interface, moving away from the striped gloss and transparency of the initial versions.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Some applications began to use a brushed metal appearance, or non-pinstriped title bar appearance in Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In Mac OS X Leopard (10.5), Apple announced a unification of the interface, with a standardized gray-gradient window style.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2006, the first Intel Macs were released with a specialized version of Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] A key development for the system was the announcement and release of the iPhone from 2007 onwards.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] While Apple's previous iPod media players used a minimal operating system, the iPhone used an operating system based on Mac OS X, which would later be called iPhone OS and then iOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The simultaneous release of two operating systems based on the same frameworks placed tension on Apple, which cited the iPhone as forcing it to delay Mac OS X Leopard.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] However, after Apple opened the iPhone to third-party developers, its commercial success drew attention to Mac OS X, with many iPhone software developers showing interest in Mac development.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2007, Mac OS X Leopard released with universal binary components, allowing installation on both Intel Macs and select PowerPC Macs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It is also the final release with PowerPC Mac support.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2009, Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6) was the first version of Mac OS X to be built exclusively for Intel Macs and the final release with 32-bit Intel Mac support.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The name was intended to signal its status as an iteration of Leopard, focusing on technical and performance improvements rather than user-facing features; indeed it was explicitly branded to developers as being a 'no new features' release.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Since its release, several OS X or macOS releases (namely OS X Mountain Lion, OS X El Capitan, macOS High Sierra, and macOS Monterey) follow this pattern, with a name derived from its predecessor, similar to the 'tick–tock model' used by Intel.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Starting in 2011 with Mac OS X Lion (10.7) and OS X Mountain Lion (10.8), Apple moved some applications to a highly skeuomorphic style of design inspired by contemporary versions of iOS while simplifying some elements by making controls such as scroll bars fade out when not in use.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In addition, with Lion, Apple ceased to release separate server versions of Mac OS X, selling server tools as a separate downloadable application through the Mac App Store.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2012, with the release of OS X Mountain Lion, the name of the system was officially shortened from Mac OS X to OS X, after the previous version shortened the system name in a similar fashion a year prior.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] That year, Apple removed the head of OS X development, Scott Forstall, and design was changed towards a more minimal direction.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple's new user interface design, using deep color saturation, text-only buttons and a minimal, 'flat' interface, was debuted with iOS 7 in 2013.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] With OS X engineers reportedly working on iOS 7, the version released in 2013, OS X Mavericks (10.9), was something of a transitional release, with some of the skeuomorphic design removed, while most of the general interface of Mavericks remained unchanged.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The next version, OS X Yosemite (10.10), adopted a design similar to iOS 7 but with greater complexity suitable for an interface controlled with a mouse.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] From 2012 onwards, the system has shifted to an annual release schedule similar to that of Mac OS X releases prior to 10.4 Tiger.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It also steadily cut the cost of updates from Snow Leopard onwards, before removing upgrade fees altogether in OS X Mavericks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Some journalists and third-party software developers have suggested that this decision, while allowing more rapid feature release, meant less opportunity to focus on stability, with no version of OS X recommendable for users requiring stability and performance above new features.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple's 2015 update, OS X El Capitan (10.11), was announced to focus specifically on stability and performance improvements.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Its successor, macOS Mojave (10.14), was released in 2018, adding a dark mode option and a dynamic wallpaper setting.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It was succeeded by macOS Catalina (10.15) in 2019, which replaces iTunes with separate apps for different types of media, and introduces the Catalyst system for porting iOS apps.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2020, Apple announced macOS Big Sur (version 11) at that year's WWDC.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This was the first increment in the primary version number of macOS since the release of Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000; updates to macOS Big Sur were given 11.x numbers, matching the version numbering scheme used by Apple's other operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Big Sur brought major changes to the user interface and was the first version to run on Apple Silicon, based on the ARM architecture.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The numbering system started with Big Sur continued in 2021 with macOS Monterey (12), 2022 with macOS Ventura (13), 2023 with macOS Sonoma (14), and 2024 with macOS Sequoia (15).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] During its Platforms State of the Union event on June 9, 2025, Apple announced that Tahoe would be the final version of macOS to operate on Intel-based Macs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2026, Apple announced macOS Golden Gate (version 27) at WWDC 2026.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It will be the first version of macOS to run exclusively on Macs with Apple silicon and the last version with full Rosetta 2 functionality.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The Power Mac G5 had special Jaguar builds.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Tiger did not support 64-bit GUI applications, only 64-bit CLI applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] 32-bit (but not 64-bit) PowerPC applications were supported on Intel processors with Rosetta.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] 64-bit Intel applications are supported on Apple silicon Macs with Rosetta 2.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] However, Intel-based Macs are unable to run ARM-based applications, such as iOS and iPadOS apps.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] At macOS's core is a POSIX-compliant operating system built on top of the XNU kernel, (which incorporated large parts of FreeBSD kernel) and FreeBSD userland for the standard Unix facilities available from the command line interface.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple has released this family of software as a free and open source operating system named Darwin.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] On top of Darwin, Apple layered a number of components, including the Aqua interface and the Finder, to complete the GUI-based operating system which is macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] With its original introduction as Mac OS X, the system brought a number of new capabilities to provide a more stable and reliable platform than its predecessor, the classic Mac OS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] For example, pre-emptive multitasking and memory protection improved the system's ability to run multiple applications simultaneously without them interrupting or corrupting each other.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Many aspects of macOS's architecture are derived from OPENSTEP, which was designed to be portable, to ease the transition from one platform to another.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] For example, NeXTSTEP was ported from the original 68k-based NeXT workstations to x86 and other architectures before NeXT was purchased by Apple, and OPENSTEP was later ported to the PowerPC architecture as part of the Rhapsody project.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Prior to macOS High Sierra, and on drives other than solid state drives (SSDs), the default file system is HFS+, which it inherited from the classic Mac OS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Operating system designer Linus Torvalds had criticized HFS+, saying it is "probably the worst file system ever", whose design is "actively corrupting user data".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] He criticized the case insensitivity of file names, a design made worse when Apple extended the file system to support Unicode.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The Darwin subsystem in macOS manages the file system, which includes the Unix permissions layer.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Later, another Macworld editor, Dan Frakes, called the procedure of repairing permissions vastly overused.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] He argues that macOS typically handles permissions properly without user interference, and resetting permissions should only be tried when problems emerge.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The architecture of macOS incorporates a layered design: the layered frameworks aid rapid development of applications by providing existing code for common tasks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple provides its own software development tools, most prominently an integrated development environment called Xcode.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Xcode provides interfaces to compilers that support several programming languages including C, C++, Objective-C, and Swift.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] For the Mac transition to Intel processors, it was modified so that developers could build their applications as a universal binary, which provides compatibility with both the Intel-based and PowerPC-based Macintosh lines.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] First and third-party applications can be controlled programmatically using the AppleScript framework, retained from the classic Mac OS, or using the newer Automator application that offers pre-written tasks that do not require programming knowledge.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple offered two main APIs to develop software natively for macOS: Cocoa and Carbon.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Cocoa was a descendant of APIs inherited from OPENSTEP with no ancestry from the classic Mac OS, while Carbon was an adaptation of classic Mac OS APIs, allowing Mac software to be minimally rewritten to run natively on Mac OS X.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The Cocoa API was created as the result of a 1993 collaboration between NeXT Computer and Sun Microsystems.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This heritage is highly visible for Cocoa developers, since the "NS" prefix is ubiquitous in the framework, standing variously for **N**eXT**S**TEP or **N**eXT/**S**un.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The official OPENSTEP API, published in September 1994, was the first to split the API between Foundation and ApplicationKit and the first to use the "NS" prefix.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Traditionally, Cocoa programs have been mostly written in Objective-C, with Java as an alternative.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Since 2014, Apple has promoted its new programming language Swift as the preferred language for software development on Apple platforms.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple's original plan with macOS was to require all developers to rewrite their software into the Cocoa APIs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This caused much outcry among existing Mac developers, who threatened to abandon the platform rather than invest in a costly rewrite, and the idea was shelved.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] To permit a smooth transition from Mac OS 9 to Mac OS X, the Carbon Application Programming Interface (API) was created.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Applications written with Carbon were initially able to run natively on both classic Mac OS and Mac OS X, although this ability was later dropped as Mac OS X developed.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Carbon was not included in the first product sold as Mac OS X: the little-used original release of Mac OS X Server 1.0, which also did not include the Aqua interface.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple limited further development of Carbon from the release of Leopard onwards and announced that Carbon applications would not run at 64-bit.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] A number of macOS applications continued to use Carbon for some time afterwards, especially ones with heritage dating back to the classic Mac OS and for which updates would be difficult, uneconomic or not necessary.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This included Microsoft Office up to Office 2016, and Photoshop up to CS5.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Early versions of macOS could also run some classic Mac OS applications through the Classic Environment with performance limitations; this feature was removed from 10.5 onwards and all Macs using Intel processors.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Because macOS is POSIX compliant, many software packages written for the other Unix-like systems including Linux can be recompiled to run on it, including many scientific and technical programs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Third-party projects such as Homebrew, Fink, MacPorts and pkgsrc provide pre-compiled or pre-formatted packages.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple and others have provided versions of the X Window System graphical interface which can allow these applications to run with an approximation of the macOS look-and-feel.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The current Apple-endorsed method is the open-source XQuartz project; earlier versions could use the X11 application provided by Apple, or before that the XDarwin project.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apps installed through the Mac App Store run within a sandbox, restricting their ability to exchange information with other applications or modify the core operating system and its features.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This has been cited as an advantage, by allowing users to install apps with confidence that they should not be able to damage their system, but also as a disadvantage due to blocking the Mac App Store's use for professional applications that require elevated privileges.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Applications without any code signature cannot be run by default except from a computer's administrator account.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Some are included with macOS and some sold separately.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This includes iWork, Final Cut Pro, Logic Pro, iLife, and the database application FileMaker.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Numerous other developers also offer software for macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2018, Apple introduced an application layer, codenamed Marzipan, to port iOS apps to macOS. macOS Mojave included ports of four first-party iOS apps including Home and News, and it was announced that the API would be available for third-party developers to use from 2019.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] With macOS Catalina in 2019, the application layer was made available to third-party developers as Mac Catalyst.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Tools such as XPostFacto and patches applied to the installation media have been developed by third parties to enable installation of newer versions of macOS on systems not officially supported by Apple.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Except for features requiring specific hardware such as graphics acceleration or DVD writing, the operating system offers the same functionality on all supported hardware.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] As most Mac hardware components, or components similar to those, since the Intel transition are available for purchase, some technology-capable groups have developed software to install macOS on non-Apple computers.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] These are referred to as Hackintoshes, a portmanteau of the words "hack" and "Macintosh".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This violates Apple's EULA (and is therefore unsupported by Apple technical support, warranties etc.), but communities that cater to personal users, who do not install for resale and profit, have generally been ignored by Apple.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] These self-made computers allow more flexibility and customization of hardware, but at a cost of leaving the user more responsible for their own machine, such as on matter of data integrity or security.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Psystar, a business that attempted to profit from selling macOS on non-Apple certified hardware, was sued by Apple in 2008.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In April 2002, eWeek announced a rumor that Apple had a version of Mac OS X code-named Marklar, which ran on Intel x86 processors.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The idea behind Marklar was to keep Mac OS X running on an alternative platform should Apple become dissatisfied with the progress of the PowerPC platform.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] These rumors subsided until late in May 2005, when various media outlets, such as *The Wall Street Journal* and CNET, announced that Apple would unveil Marklar in the coming months.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] On June 6, 2005, Steve Jobs announced in his keynote address at WWDC that Apple would be making the transition from PowerPC to Intel processors over the following two years, and that Mac OS X would support both platforms during the transition.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Jobs also confirmed rumors that Apple had versions of Mac OS X running on Intel processors for most of its developmental life.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Intel-based Macs would run a new recompiled version of OS X along with Rosetta, a binary translation layer which enables software compiled for PowerPC Mac OS X to run on Intel Mac OS X machines.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The system was included with Mac OS X versions up to version 10.6.8.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple dropped support for Classic mode on the new Intel Macs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Third party emulation software such as Mini vMac, Basilisk II and SheepShaver provided support for some early versions of Mac OS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] A new version of Xcode and the underlying command-line compilers supported building universal binaries that would run on either architecture.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] PowerPC-only software is supported with Apple's official binary translation software, Rosetta, though applications eventually had to be rewritten to run properly on the newer versions released for Intel processors.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple initially encouraged developers to produce universal binaries with support for both PowerPC and Intel.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] PowerPC binaries suffer a performance penalty when run on Intel Macs through Rosetta.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Moreover, some PowerPC software, such as kernel extensions and System Preferences plugins, are not supported on Intel Macs at all.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Plugins for Safari need to be compiled for the same platform as Safari, so when Safari is running on Intel, it requires plug-ins that have been compiled as Intel-only or universal binaries, so PowerPC-only plug-ins will not work.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] While Intel Macs can run PowerPC, Intel, and universal binaries, PowerPC Macs support only universal and PowerPC builds.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Support for the PowerPC platform was dropped following the transition.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2009, Apple announced at WWDC that Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard would drop support for PowerPC processors and be Intel-only.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Rosetta continued to be offered as an optional download or installation choice in Snow Leopard before it was discontinued with Mac OS X 10.7 Lion.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In addition, new versions of Mac OS X first- and third-party software increasingly required Intel processors, including new versions of iLife, iWork, Aperture and Logic Pro.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Rumors of Apple shifting Macs from Intel to in-house ARM processors used by iOS devices began circulating as early as 2011, and ebbed and flowed throughout the 2010s.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Rumors intensified in 2020, when numerous reports announced that the company would announce its shift to its custom processors at WWDC.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple officially announced its shift to processors designed in-house on June 22, 2020, at WWDC 2020, with the transition planned to last for approximately two years.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The first release of macOS to support ARM was macOS Big Sur.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Big Sur and later versions support Universal 2 binaries, which are applications consisting of both Intel (x86-64) and Apple silicon (AArch64) binaries; when launched, only the appropriate binary is run.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Additionally, Intel binaries can be run on Apple silicon-based Macs using the Rosetta 2 binary translation software.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The transition was completed at WWDC 2023 with the announcement of the Apple silicon Mac Pro, ending the transition in 3 years, slightly behind schedule.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The change in processor architecture allows Macs with ARM processors to be able to run iOS and iPadOS apps natively.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The macOS user interface places a menu bar along the top edge of the screen, containing the Apple menu and application menus at the start, and status menus at the end.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The Dock is placed along the bottom of the screen by default, and contains icons for pinned and active applications, file and folder shortcuts, minimized windows, and the Trash (or Bin).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] On most windows, the start of the title bar has three buttons resembling a horizontal traffic light, which respectively close, minimize, and resize the window.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple has continued to change aspects of the macOS appearance and design, particularly with tweaks to the appearance of windows and the menu bar.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Since 2012, Apple has sold almost all of its Mac models with high-resolution Retina displays, and macOS and its APIs have extensive support for resolution-independent development on supporting high-resolution displays.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Reviewers have described Apple's support for the technology as superior to that on Windows.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The human interface guidelines published by Apple for macOS are followed by many applications, giving them consistent user interface and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Services available in every Cocoa application include spelling and grammar checkers, special characters palette, color picker, font chooser and dictionary.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The graphics system OpenGL composites windows onto the screen to allow hardware-accelerated drawing.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] This technology, introduced in version 10.2, is called Quartz Extreme, a component of Quartz.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Quartz's internal imaging model correlates well with the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, making it easy to output PDF to multiple devices.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] As a side result, PDF viewing and creating PDF documents from any application are built-in features.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Reflecting its popularity with design users, macOS also has system support for a variety of professional video and image formats and includes an extensive pre-installed font library, featuring many prominent brand-name designs.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] A major addition between the classic Mac OS and the first major release of Mac OS X was Aqua, a design language with water-like elements.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Every window element, text, graphic, or widget was drawn on-screen using spatial anti-aliasing technology.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The preexisting ColorSync technology was improved and built into the core drawing engine, to provide color matching for printing and multimedia professionals.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Drop shadows were added around windows and isolated text elements to provide a sense of depth.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] New interface elements were integrated, including sheets (dialog boxes attached to specific windows) and drawers, which would slide out and provide options.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The use of soft edges, translucent colors, and pinstripes, similar to the hardware design of the first iMacs, brought more texture and color to the user interface when compared to what Mac OS 9 and Mac OS X Server 1.0's Platinum appearance had offered.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Third-party developers started producing skins for customizable applications and other operating systems which mimicked the Aqua appearance.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] To some extent, Apple has used the successful transition to this design as leverage, at various times threatening legal action against people who make or distribute software with an interface the company says is derived from its copyrighted design.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Following a similar design change in iOS 7, OS X Yosemite shifted to a flat design language, simplifying many of the Aqua elements and icons.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In 2025, macOS Tahoe adopted the Liquid Glass design language, which was inspired in part by Aqua.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The Finder is a file browser allowing quick access to all areas of the computer, which has been modified throughout subsequent releases of macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Quick Look has been part of the Finder since version 10.5.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] It allows for dynamic previews of files, including videos and multi-page documents without opening any other applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Spotlight, a file searching technology which has been integrated into the Finder since version 10.4, allows rapid real-time searches of data files; mail messages; photos; and other information based on item properties (metadata) or content.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple added Exposé in version 10.3 (called Mission Control since version 10.7), a feature which includes three functions to help accessibility between windows and desktop.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Its functions are to instantly reveal all open windows as thumbnails for easy navigation to different tasks, display all open windows as thumbnails from the current application, and hide all windows to access the desktop.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] FileVault is optional encryption of the user's files with the 128-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-128).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Sync Services allows applications to access a centralized extensible database for various elements of user data, including calendar and contact items.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] The operating system then managed conflicting edits and data consistency.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple has developed support for emoji characters by including the proprietary Apple Color Emoji font.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple has also connected macOS with social networks such as Twitter and Facebook through the addition of share buttons for content such as pictures and text.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Apple has brought several applications and features that originally debuted in iOS, its mobile operating system, to macOS, notably the intelligent personal assistant Siri, which was introduced in version 10.12 of macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] There are 47 system languages available in macOS for the user at the moment of installation; the system language is used throughout the entire operating system environment.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Input methods for typing in dozens of scripts can be chosen independently of the system language.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Updates have added increased support for Chinese characters and interconnections with popular social networks in China.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] macOS can be updated using the Software Update settings pane in System Settings or the `softwareupdate` command line utility.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Until OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion, a separate Software Update application performed this functionality.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In Mountain Lion and later, this was merged into the Mac App Store application, although the underlying update mechanism remains unchanged and is fundamentally different from the download mechanism used when purchasing an App Store application.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] In macOS 10.14 Mojave, the updating function was moved again to the Software Update settings pane.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] Most Macs receive six or seven years of macOS updates.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p01] After a new major release of macOS, the previous two releases still receive occasional updates, but many security vulnerabilities are only patched in the latest macOS release.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X versions were named after big cats, with the exception of Mac OS X Server 1.0 and the original public beta, from Mac OS X 10.0 until OS X 10.9 Mavericks, when Apple switched to using California locations.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Prior to its release, version 10.0 was code named internally at Apple as "Cheetah", and Mac OS X 10.1 was code named internally as "Puma".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] After the immense buzz surrounding Mac OS X 10.2, codenamed "Jaguar", Apple's product marketing began openly using the code names to promote the operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.3 was marketed as "Panther", Mac OS X 10.4 as "Tiger", Mac OS X 10.5 as "Leopard", Mac OS X 10.6 as "Snow Leopard", Mac OS X 10.7 as "Lion", OS X 10.8 as "Mountain Lion", and OS X 10.9 as "Mavericks".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] "Panther", "Tiger" and "Leopard" are registered as trademarks of Apple, but "Cheetah", "Puma" and "Jaguar" have never been registered.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple has also registered "Lynx" and "Cougar" as trademarks, though these were allowed to lapse.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Computer retailer Tiger Direct sued Apple for its use of the name "Tiger".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On May 16, 2005, a US federal court in the Southern District of Florida ruled that Apple's use did not infringe on Tiger Direct's trademark.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On September 13, 2000, Apple released a US$29.95 "preview" version of Mac OS X, internally codenamed Kodiak, to gain feedback from users.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The "PB", as it was known, marked the first public availability of the Aqua interface and Apple made many changes to the UI based on customer feedback.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X Public Beta expired and ceased to function in Spring 2001.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On March 24, 2001, Apple released Mac OS X 10.0 (internally codenamed Cheetah).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The initial version was slow, incomplete, and had very few applications available at launch, mostly from independent developers.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] While many critics suggested that the operating system was not ready for mainstream adoption, they recognized the importance of its initial launch as a base on which to improve.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Simply releasing Mac OS X was received by the Macintosh community as a great accomplishment, for attempts to overhaul the Mac OS had been underway since 1996, and had been delayed by countless setbacks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Later that year, on September 25, 2001, Mac OS X 10.1 (internally codenamed Puma) was released.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It featured increased performance and provided missing features, such as DVD playback.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple released 10.1 as a free upgrade CD for 10.0 users, in addition to the $129 boxed version for people running Mac OS 9.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It was discovered that the upgrade CDs were full install CDs that could be used with Mac OS 9 systems by removing a specific file; Apple later re-released the CDs in an actual stripped-down format that did not facilitate installation on such systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On January 7, 2002, Apple announced that Mac OS X was to be the default operating system for all Macintosh products by the end of that month.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On August 23, 2002, Apple followed up with Mac OS X 10.2 Jaguar, the first release to use its code name as part of the branding.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It brought significant performance improvements, and an updated version of Aqua's visual design.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The Happy Mac icon — which had appeared during the Mac OS startup sequence since the original Macintosh — was replaced with a gray Apple logo.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X v10.3 Panther was released on October 24, 2003.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It significantly improved performance and incorporated the most extensive update yet to the user interface.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Support for some early G3 computers such as "beige" Power Macs and "WallStreet" PowerBooks was discontinued.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger was released on April 29, 2005.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple stated that Tiger contained more than 200 new features.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] As with Panther, certain older machines were no longer supported; Tiger requires a Mac with 256 MB of RAM and a built-in FireWire port.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Among the new features, Tiger introduced Spotlight, Dashboard, Smart Folders, updated Mail program with Smart Mailboxes, QuickTime 7, Safari 2, Automator, VoiceOver, Core Image and Core Video.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The initial release of the Apple TV used a modified version of Tiger with a different graphical interface and fewer applications and services.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] On January 10, 2006, Apple released the first Intel-based Macs along with the 10.4.4 update to Tiger.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] This operating system functioned identically on the PowerPC-based Macs and the new Intel-based machines, with the exception of the Intel release lacking support for the Classic environment.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard was released on October 26, 2007.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It was called by Apple "the largest update of Mac OS X".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Leopard supports both PowerPC- and Intel x86-based Macintosh computers; support for the G3 processor was dropped and the G4 processor required a minimum clock rate of 867 MHz, and at least 512 MB of RAM to be installed.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The single DVD works for all supported Macs (including 64-bit machines).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] New features include a new look, an updated Finder, Time Machine, Spaces, Boot Camp pre-installed, full support for 64-bit applications (including graphical applications), new features in Mail and iChat, and a number of new security features.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Leopard is an Open Brand UNIX 03 registered product on the Intel platform.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It was also the first BSD-based OS to receive UNIX 03 certification.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Leopard dropped support for the Classic Environment and all Classic applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It was the final version of Mac OS X to support the PowerPC architecture.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard was released on August 28, 2009.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Rather than delivering big changes to the appearance and end user functionality like the previous releases of Mac OS X, Snow Leopard focused on "under the hood" changes, increasing the performance, efficiency, and stability of the operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Snow Leopard only supported machines with Intel CPUs, required at least 1 GB of RAM, and dropped default support for applications built for the PowerPC architecture (Rosetta could be installed as an additional component to retain support for PowerPC-only applications).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Snow Leopard also featured new 64-bit technology capable of supporting greater amounts of RAM, improved support for multi-core processors through Grand Central Dispatch, and advanced GPU performance with OpenCL.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The 10.6.6 update also introduced support for the Mac App Store, Apple's digital distribution platform for macOS applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.7 Lion was released on July 20, 2011.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It brought developments made in Apple's iOS, such as an easily navigable display of installed applications called Launchpad and a greater use of multi-touch gestures, to the Mac.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] This release removed Rosetta, making it incompatible with PowerPC applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Changes made to the GUI include auto-hiding scrollbars that only appear when they are used, and Mission Control which unifies Exposé, Spaces, Dashboard, and full-screen applications within a single interface.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple also made changes to applications: they resume in the same state as they were before they were closed, similar to iOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion was released on July 25, 2012.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Following the release of Lion the previous year, it was the first of the annual rather than two-yearly updates to OS X (and later macOS), which also closely aligned with the annual iOS operating system updates.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It incorporates some features seen in iOS 5, which include Game Center, support for iMessage in the new Messages messaging application, and Reminders as a to-do list app separate from iCal (which is renamed as Calendar, like the iOS app).
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It also includes support for storing iWork documents in iCloud.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Notification Center, which makes its debut in Mountain Lion, is a desktop version similar to the one in iOS 5.0 and higher.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Application pop-ups are now concentrated on the corner of the screen, and the Center itself is pulled from the right side of the screen.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mountain Lion also includes more Chinese features including support for Baidu as an option for Safari search engine, QQ, 163.com and 126.com services for Mail, Contacts and Calendar, Youku, Tudou and Sina Weibo are integrated into share sheets.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Starting with Mountain Lion, Apple software updates (including the OS) are distributed via the App Store.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] This updating mechanism replaced the Apple Software Update utility.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.9 Mavericks was released on October 22, 2013.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It is a free upgrade to all users running Snow Leopard or later with a 64-bit Intel processor.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Its changes include the addition of the previously iOS-only Maps and iBooks applications, improvements to the Notification Center, enhancements to several applications, and many under-the-hood improvements.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.10 Yosemite was released on October 16, 2014.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It features a redesigned user interface similar to that of iOS 7, intended to feature a more minimal, text-based 'flat' design, with use of translucency effects and intensely saturated colors.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple's showcase new feature in Yosemite is Handoff, which enables users with iPhones running iOS 8.1 or later to answer phone calls, receive and send SMS messages, and complete unfinished iPhone emails on their Mac.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] As of OS X 10.10.3, Photos replaced iPhoto and Aperture.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] OS X 10.11 El Capitan was released on September 30, 2015.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Similar to Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard, Apple described this release as emphasizing "refinements to the Mac experience" and "improvements to system performance".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Refinements include public transport built into the Maps application, GUI improvements to the Notes application, adopting San Francisco as the system font for clearer legibility, and the introduction of System Integrity Protection.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The Metal API, first introduced in iOS 8, was also included in this operating system for "all Macs since 2012".
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] According to Apple, Metal accelerates system-level rendering by up to 50 percent, resulting in faster graphics performance for everyday apps.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Metal also delivers up to 10 times faster draw call performance for more fluid experience in games and pro apps.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.12 Sierra was released to the public on September 20, 2016.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] New features include the addition of Siri, optimized storage, and updates to Photos, Messages, and iTunes.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra was released to the public on September 25, 2017.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Like OS X El Capitan and OS X Mountain Lion, High Sierra is a refinement-based update having very few new features visible to the user, including updates to Safari, Photos, and Mail, among other changes.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The major change under the hood is the switch to the Apple File System, optimized for the solid-state storage used in most new Mac computers.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.14 Mojave was released on September 24, 2018.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The update introduced a system-wide dark mode and several new apps lifted from iOS, such as Apple News.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It was the first version to require a GPU that supports Metal.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mojave also changed the system software update mechanism from the App Store (where it had been since OS X Mountain Lion) to a new panel in System Preferences.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS 10.15 Catalina was released on October 7, 2019.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Updates included enhanced voice control, and bundled apps for music, video, and podcasts that together replace the functions of iTunes, and the ability to use an iPad as an external monitor.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Catalina officially dropped support for 32-bit applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Big Sur was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 22, 2020, and it was made available to the general public on November 12, 2020.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] This is the first time the major version number of the operating system has been incremented since the Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It brings Arm support, new icons, and aesthetic user interface changes to the system.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Ventura was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 6, 2022 and released on October 24, 2022.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It came with the redesigned System Preferences (named System Settings) to a more iOS-like design, and the new Freeform, Weather and Clock apps that run natively on Mac.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Users can use an iPhone as a webcam for video conferencing with Continuity Camera.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Siri's appearance was changed to look more like the versions on iOS 14 and iPadOS 14.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Mail introduced schedule send and undo send for emails, and Message also got the ability to undo send and edit messages.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Stage Manager was introduced as a new way to organize all open windows in a desktop.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Maps gained the feature for multiple-stop routes, Metal 3 was added with support for spatial and temporal image upscaling, Lockdown Mode was added to reduce the risk of a cyberattack, and the ability to play ambient background sounds was added as an accessibility feature in System Settings.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Sonoma was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 5, 2023, and released on September 26, 2023. macOS Sonoma revamped widgets—they can now be placed anywhere on the desktop.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Game mode optimizes game performance by prioritizing gaming tasks and allocating more GPU and CPU capacity to the game, and by doing so is able to provide smoother frame rates for gameplay.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The Spotlight Search bar and all app icons were made even more rounded, smoother animations were implemented for notifications and the lock screen, and new slow-motion screensavers of different locations worldwide were added.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] When logged in, they gradually slow down and become the desktop wallpaper.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Sequoia was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 10, 2024.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Tahoe was announced on June 9, 2025, during the WWDC 2025 keynote address.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It is the first macOS version to feature the new Liquid Glass design introduced across Apple operating systems that year.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It is also the first macOS to use Apple's new release number convention, which gives all of Apple's operating systems the same version number.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Golden Gate was announced at WWDC on June 8, 2026.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] It introduces visual intelligence, redesigns Siri, and brings Apple Intelligence features to apps such as Safari and Passwords.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Golden Gate also improves Liquid Glass on windows and sidebars, and allows users to adjust the system opacity.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple publishes Apple Platform Security documents to lay out the security protections built into macOS and Mac hardware.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] These prevent some vulnerabilities within macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Only the latest major release of macOS (macOS Tahoe as of June 2026) receives patches for all known security vulnerabilities.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] The previous two releases receive some security updates, but not for all vulnerabilities known to Apple.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] macOS Ventura added support for Rapid Security Response (RSR) updates and Lockdown Mode.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Rapid Security Response updates may require a reboot, but take less than a minute to install.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] In an analysis, Hackintosh developer Mykola Grymalyuk noted that RSR updates can only fix userland vulnerabilities, and cannot patch the macOS kernel.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Lockdown Mode is an optional security feature designed to provide extreme protection for users who may be at risk of targeted cyberattacks, such as journalists, activists, and public figures.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] This mode significantly alters the functionality of the device to enhance security against sophisticated threats, particularly from spyware and state-sponsored attacks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple says most people are never impacted by these attacks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] In its earlier years, Mac OS X enjoyed a near-absence of the types of malware and spyware that have affected Microsoft Windows users. macOS has a smaller usage share compared to Windows.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Worms, as well as potential vulnerabilities, were noted in 2006, which led some industry analysts and anti-virus companies to issue warnings that Apple's Mac OS X is not immune to malware.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Increasing market share coincided with additional reports of a variety of attacks.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] In early 2011, Mac OS X experienced a large increase in malware attacks, and malware such as Mac Defender, MacProtector, and MacGuard was seen as an increasing problem for Mac users.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] At first, the malware installer required the user to enter the administrative password, but later versions installed without user input.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Initially, Apple support staff were instructed not to assist in the removal of the malware or admit the existence of the malware issue, but as the malware spread, a support document was issued.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple announced an OS X update to fix the problem.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] An estimated 100,000 users were affected.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] Apple releases security updates for macOS regularly, as well as signature files containing malware signatures for Xprotect, an anti-malware feature part of File Quarantine present since Mac OS X Snow Leopard.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] As of January 2023, macOS is the second-most widely used general-purpose desktop operating system used on the World Wide Web following Microsoft Windows, with a 15.33% usage share, according to statistics compiled by StatCounter.
[src:homebrew-macos/macos-p02] As a device company, Apple has mostly promoted macOS to sell Macs, with promotion of macOS updates focused on existing users, promotion at Apple Store and other retail partners, or through events for developers.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts supports universal binaries for PowerPC, Intel-based, and Apple silicon versions of macOS, but migrating from a PowerPC installation of MacPorts to a version on an Intel Mac requires reinstalling all installed ports.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] As an example, one common task is to update outdated ports.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts supports logical operators such as *and*, *or* and *not,* as well as glob patterns (enabled by default) and regex (enabled via `--regex`).
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Users can indicate one or more packages that they wish to install via the `install` mode, and MacPorts will aim to install them and its dependencies.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Note that this will install the latest version as indicated by the local ports tree.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Running `selfupdate` beforehand will make sure that the downloaded package is the newest version in MacPorts.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Variants provide different options that may be invoked when installing a port.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Common actions include adding or removing dependencies and changing build arguments.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They provide additional functionality that might not necessarily be useful for all users, but can be useful for others.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] For instance, the youtube-dl port provides an ffmpeg variant that is enabled by default.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] In return for adding two extra dependencies, this then allows for audio to be extracted.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Multiple variants can be listed one after another by separating them with a space.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The variants of a port can be determined by running `port variants *packagename*`, or by searching for the port on the MacPorts website.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The MacPorts Ports website was implemented during Google Summer of Code 2019, with major UI improvements made within the same program in 2020.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It displays information about individual ports, such as installation statistics and build-history.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] These statistics are also available via an API.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Users can optionally login to be notified when a port has been updated.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] There is also a separate MacPorts homepage, that provides information on the project as well as instructions on how to install it.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts was started in 2002 with the involvement of a number of Apple Inc. employees, including Landon Fuller, Kevin Van Vechten, and Jordan Hubbard.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It was originally known as DarwinPorts, with the name coming from Darwin and FreeBSD Ports.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It began as part of the OpenDarwin project, with its aim to help users on macOS and Darwin to install Unix software.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] DarwinPorts was then hosted on Mac OS Forge, an open source hosting service created and maintained by Apple Inc. for third-party projects not supported by Apple.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] So as to indicate the project's emphasis on macOS, its name was changed to MacPorts.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] When Apple closed Mac OS Forge in 2016, the project moved to GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] As part of this change, git was used as the new version control system, although Trac was still preferred for ticket management over GitHub issues.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Version 1.0 was released on April 28, 2005.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] In December 2005 the project reached a milestone, surpassing 3,000 ports.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] At that time, package installation involved the source code being downloaded and compiled on the end user's machine.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Version 2.0, released in 2011, introduced support for prebuilt binary archives; by default ports are installed using the prebuilt binary archive if available, and are built from source otherwise.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] As of May 2023, MacPorts has over 33,600 ports and best-effort support can be sourced from the community.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts installs software on top of the operating system, providing newer versions of pre-installed packages or software that is not included in macOS.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This is in contrast to other package management systems, such as APT and DNF, that are part of the operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] For this reason, MacPorts is sometimes known as an overlay distribution.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Other examples include Fink and Homebrew.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] In contrast to the FreeBSD Ports Collection, which installs its software in `/usr/local`, MacPorts stores its data in `/opt/local` by default, although this can be modified when compiling MacPorts from source.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The reason given for this change is that other packaging systems could overwrite what MacPorts has installed, or vice versa.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] A dedicated directory helps to overcome this problem.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Fink follows a similar approach, installing its data into `/sw` by default.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Buildbots are used to build ports in advance so that users do not have to compile the package locally.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The result of this is known as a binary archive, and it helps to reduce the time required for installation.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Similar to Homebrew, MacPorts takes the approach of having different builders for different operating system versions and architectures.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] However, sometimes it might be necessary to build from source locally if the binaries fail to build or the port's license does not allow binary distribution.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] If a binary could not be built, this would be noted on the MacPorts website for that individual port and the maintainer would be alerted.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It is also possible to view recent buildbot events on a dedicated activity page.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Binary archives are created locally whenever a user builds a port from source.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They can also be manually created by running `sudo port archive *packagename*`.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts stores the instructions required to build a port in a port description file, otherwise known as a portfile.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This is similar to how the AUR use shell scripts known as a PKGBUILD, or how Homebrew use ruby scripts as a formula.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The portfiles are complete TCL programs with access to the TCL interpreter.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They make use of simple *key value* pair options to define attributes.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Each portfile has pre-defined stages that can be manually configured via the portfile.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] First, MacPorts retrieves and downloads all the relevant files for the port from upstream.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] In the case of hashcat, these files are retrieved from GitHub.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They are removed, along with temporary build files, when the installation is complete.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Checksums are always defined within the portfile, since they are different for different files.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The checksums of the downloaded files are compared to those in the portfile to see whether they match.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Only one compressed file is downloaded for Hashcat, so only one checksum is required in the portfile.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Sometimes, the code might need to be modified to make it installable via MacPorts.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This could be for a variety of reasons, such as it installing in the wrong location by default.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Patch files can be used to modify the source code in a readable format.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] In the above portfile, Hashcat does not require any changes to the code for the installation to work.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Hence, there are no patch files required.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The project's configure script is run to prepare for the build process.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Part of this involves determining whether the required libraries are present.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] For ports that do not have a configure script, this stage (as well as others when required) can be disabled.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Since the configure stage is not referenced in the Portfile, hashcat is using the default configure setup as defined by MacPorts.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This involves running the configure script via `./configure`.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The instructions in the portfile are then used to build the port.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The commands that are executed can vary for different languages.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The portfile for hashcat shows that it should be treated as a Makefile project.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It will therefore be built by running `make`.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Some ports define a test to verify that the build has succeeded.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This is an optional phase that is only run if the user executes `port test *packagename*`.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] It is therefore not executed when installing a port.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This hashcat port has not defined a test stage.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The destroot stage is the first step in moving the built files into the correct location.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] MacPorts takes the approach of first staging the installation into an intermediate location (destroot) before placing the files in their correct positions (install).
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] One advantage of this is that it makes it easy to record what files were created, allowing them to be cleanly uninstalled.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] As an example, a file that would normally be installed to `/opt/local/lib/libfoo.a` might first be installed to `/tmp/stage/opt/local/lib/libfoo.a` during the destroot stage, maintaining the relative directory structure.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] For hashcat, this is done by running `make install`, where one of the arguments (`DESTDIR`) specifies where to temporarily store the files.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Note that in the majority of scenarios, only the stages below occur on the user's machine.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This is because binaries for the ports are pre-built so that they do not need to be built from source locally.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The destrooted files are archived safely.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Since these files have not been activated yet, this allows for multiple different versions of the same port to be archived without interfering with each other.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] When activating a port, the files in the destroot directory are moved to their correct location.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This makes them accessible to the user, completing the installation process.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] If they wish to try a different version of the port, they can deactivate their current version and activate the new one.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This does not uninstall the old port since it can easily be activated again from the archived files.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] When upgrading a port, MacPorts deactivates but does not uninstall the current version as a safety feature.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This allows the user to easily revert to the old version if the update causes breaking changes.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Packages are the responsibility of individual maintainers, who are mentioned within the portfile.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They are expected to update the port and apply bug-fixes where required.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Anybody who wants to modify a portfile should alert the maintainer before applying the changes, although this is not always required for minor modifications.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Anyone is able to contribute to MacPorts, generally via pull requests, and contributors can apply for commit rights following a good track record as a maintainer.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] A team of MacPorts members, known as the project managers, help to lead and coordinate the project.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Starting from 2016, meetings have occasionally been held once a year.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] They normally take place in Slovenia, and allow for MacPorts members to work on future development.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] By default, MacPorts does not collect any statistics.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] However, users can optionally submit information by running `sudo port install mpstats`.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] This sends details once a week on which ports are installed, as well as various system properties.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] The information is then used to determine which hardware to support and to understand how quickly new MacPorts releases are adopted.
[src:homebrew-macos/macports] Users can view analytics data on the MacPorts website.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:homebrew-macos/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:homebrew-macos/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:homebrew-macos/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
